## Plot data {#sec-plot_data_ve}

[↑ top](#)

- Plot a scatter plot using `ggplot()` and `geom_point()` with longitude on the x axis and latitude on the y axis.
- Add a map to the plot using `annotation_borders()` and `coord_quickmap()`.
- Set axis limits by subtracting `2` from the minimum longitude and latitude and adding `2` to the maximum longitude and latitude\`. If your study covers a small geographic area, you may find that adding 2 degrees leaves too much empty space. Adjust these values if necessary.

:::  {.callout-note}

Some of the geographic areas are very small so you might not actually see many borders on your plot - don't worry about this.

:::

- Colour the points by individual by adding `aes(color = individual_local_identifier))` as an argument to `geom_point()`.
- If you wish, change the appearance of your plot to your taste.

### Example solution

::: {#ex-plot_data_ans .callout-answer collapse="true"}
- Plot a scatter plot using `ggplot()` and `geom_point()` with longitude on the x axis and latitude on the y axis.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(
  loc_sum,
  aes(
    x = Longitude,
    y = Latitude,
  )
) +
  geom_point()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](02-04_visualisation_exercise_files/figure-html/plot_data_ans1-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


- Add a map to the plot using `annotation_borders()` and `coord_quickmap()`.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(
  loc_sum,
  aes(
    x = Longitude,
    y = Latitude,
  )
) +
  geom_point() +
  annotation_borders(linewidth = 0.2) +
  coord_quickmap()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](02-04_visualisation_exercise_files/figure-html/plot_data_ans2-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


- Set axis limits by subtracting `2` from the minimum longitude and latitude and adding `2` to the maximum longitude and latitude`. If`2\` seems like too little or too much for your data, feel free to adjust.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
min_lat <- loc_sum |>
  pull(Latitude) |>
  min()

max_lat <- loc_sum |>
  pull(Latitude) |>
  max()

min_lon <- loc_sum |>
  pull(Longitude) |>
  min()

max_lon <- loc_sum |>
  pull(Longitude) |>
  max()


ggplot(
  loc_sum,
  aes(
    x = Longitude,
    y = Latitude,
  )
) +
  geom_point() +
  annotation_borders(
    linewidth = 0.2
  ) +
  coord_quickmap(
    # as my data has a narrow y range I have used 0.2 instead of 2
    xlim = c(min_lon - 2, max_lon + 2),
    ylim = c(min_lat - 0.2, max_lat + 0.2)
  )
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](02-04_visualisation_exercise_files/figure-html/plot_data_ans3-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


- Colour the points by individual by adding `color = individual_local_identifier` to the `aes` function.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(
  loc_sum,
  aes(
    x = Longitude,
    y = Latitude,
    color = individual_local_identifier
  )
) +
  geom_point() +
  annotation_borders(
    linewidth = 0.2
  ) +
  coord_quickmap(
    xlim = c(min_lon - 2, max_lon + 2),
    ylim = c(min_lat - 0.2, max_lat + 0.2)
  )
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](02-04_visualisation_exercise_files/figure-html/plot_data_ans4-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


- If you wish, change the appearance of your plot to your taste.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(
  loc_sum,
  aes(
    x = Longitude,
    y = Latitude,
    color = individual_local_identifier
  )
) +
  geom_point() +
  annotation_borders(
    linewidth = 0.2
  ) +
  coord_quickmap(
    xlim = c(min_lon - 2, max_lon + 2),
    ylim = c(min_lat - 0.2, max_lat + 0.2)
  ) +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
  theme_bw()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](02-04_visualisation_exercise_files/figure-html/plot_data_ans5-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::

